        <div id="collapseEmotional" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="headingEmotional" data-parent="#laws-section">
            <div class="card-body">
                <p>Emotional abuse laws protect individuals from psychological harm, manipulation, and controlling behavior. Key legal provisions include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Protection from Harassment Act</li>
                    <li>Domestic Violence laws addressing emotional manipulation</li>
                </ul>
                <h4>The Constitution of India and Emotional Abuse</h4>
                <p>
                    The Constitution of India does not explicitly mention "emotional abuse" in specific articles. However, several constitutional provisions create a framework that indirectly addresses and protects against emotional abuse, particularly by upholding principles of dignity, equality, and protection from discrimination. Here’s a detailed look at how these constitutional provisions relate to the protection of women from emotional abuse:
                </p>
                <h4>Key Constitutional Provisions</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Article 15(1)</b>: Prohibits discrimination by the State against any citizen on grounds such as sex. This provision ensures that women are not subjected to discriminatory practices, including emotional abuse.</li>
                    <li><b>Article 21</b>: Guarantees the right to life and personal liberty, interpreted by the Supreme Court to include the right to live with dignity. Emotional abuse, affecting mental and emotional well-being, falls under this right.</li>
                    <li><b>Article 14</b>: Guarantees equality before the law and equal protection of the laws, ensuring all individuals, including women, receive legal protection against emotional abuse.</li>
                    <li><b>Article 39(a)</b>: States that men and women should have equal rights to an adequate means of livelihood. Economic stability indirectly supports protection from emotional abuse.</li>
                    <li><b>Article 46</b>: Promotes the educational and economic interests of weaker sections, including women, indirectly supporting protection against emotional abuse.</li>
                    <li><b>Article 51A(e)</b>: Requires every citizen to renounce practices derogatory to the dignity of women, fostering a cultural environment that opposes emotional abuse.</li>
                </ul>
                <h4>Specific Legislation and Judicial Interpretations</h4>
                <p>
                    While these constitutional articles provide a broad protective framework, specifics are outlined in legislation and judicial interpretations:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005</b>: Provides specific protection against various forms of abuse, including emotional or psychological abuse within domestic settings.</li>
                    <li><b>Sexual Harassment of Women at Workplace (Prevention, Prohibition, and Redressal) Act, 2013</b>: Addresses emotional and psychological harassment in the workplace.</li>
                    <li><b>Judicial Interpretations</b>: The Supreme Court of India has interpreted Article 21 to include protection from emotional distress, recognizing its impact on dignity and mental health.</li>
                </ul>
