    <div id="collapseStalking" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="headingStalking" data-parent="#laws-section">
        <div class="card-body">
            <p>Stalking involves unwanted and repeated following, contacting, or monitoring of an individual, whether physically or digitally. Indian laws provide protection against both physical and cyberstalking:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Section 354D of the Indian Penal Code (IPC):</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Defines stalking as repeatedly following or contacting a woman despite her disinterest or monitoring her activities online (cyberstalking).</li>
                        <li>Punishment:
                            <ul>
                                <li>First-time offenders: Imprisonment up to 3 years and/or a fine.</li>
                                <li>Repeat offenders: Imprisonment up to 5 years and a fine.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>The Information Technology (IT) Act, 2000 (Amended in 2008):</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Addresses cyberstalking and online harassment.</li>
                        <li><strong>Section 67:</strong> Penalizes electronically publishing or transmitting obscene material, which may include cyberstalking.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>These laws aim to ensure the safety and dignity of individuals against physical and cyberstalking.</p>
            <h4>Constitutional Provisions Addressing Stalking:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Article 15(1):</strong> Prohibits discrimination based on gender, ensuring protection from harassment.</li>
                <li><strong>Article 21:</strong> Guarantees the right to life and personal liberty, which includes protection from stalking.</li>
                <li><strong>Article 14:</strong> Ensures equality before the law and equal protection against crimes like stalking.</li>
                <li><strong>Article 39(a):</strong> Promotes gender equality and indirectly supports protection from harassment.</li>
                <li><strong>Article 51A(e):</strong> Calls for renunciation of practices derogatory to the dignity of women, discouraging stalking behaviors.</li>
            </ul>
